{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
I am looking on your web pages for a top level description of what stash plugins do (as I am a potential plugin developer). Do they get activated when certain operations are performed? What operations? What is the interface to stash, is there command line program to do the same functions available in the web interface (for stash and other tools)? What is the basic mechanism of the plugin system? Interpret some XML file? What kind of actions can be performed via plugins? Create some kind of output in html?, change the files as they go in and out of repository?, execute sequences of stash (or other tool) operations? (what operations?) Do plugins need to be web based?

I don't see how anyone can get the idea that some function could be done with a custom plugin without some basic description of what operations exist and how they are invoked. Saying "GIT hooks" means nothing to some user/developer migrating from an SVN based system like TeamForge. Just showing a list of user contributed plugins is also not very helpful.

Why isn't there some basic description of plugins on the top level plugin web page or some other obvious, EASILY ACCESSIBLE place? like under the "about" menu or on the top level page?

Also your naming of tools really obscures their functions. It is confusing for new users to have to memorize them. I would think that something like atlassian-collab, atlassian-repo, atlassian-what-ever-it-does with command line programs like a-colab a-rep, etc (assuming you have command line programs)., would be much better.

What the heck is it?
{panel}

